<font color="#FF0000">DRUG USE IN VIET NAM</font><br>
<tt>Fri Sep 26 23:12:47 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I was stationed at Phu Loi, an airfield about an hour's drive north of Long Binh, 1971-1972. No doubt marijuana was easily available and probably anything a guy may have been willing to buy. I recall seeing plenty of the little plastic screw top vials littering the ground, rumored to have contained heroin. The post commander's driver dissappeared into the military justice system because he got caught using drugs. I was too cautious to go that route and stuck with the alcohol easily available at the PX. One of the E-6's assigned to our group would regularly get pickled. I didn't touch the illegal drugs until after returning to the states.<br><br>
Since returning I have met a couple of veterans who had been in Cambodia, one who was captured and escaped, who refer to having been drug induced to &quot;forget&quot; their experiences, by U.S. army medical personnel. How's that for a shift in thinking about the use of drugs during the American war on Viet Nam.
<p><code>-- ldowney@media.utah.edu  (Lewis Downey) </code><p>


